Harry Potter Episode 3 - Sorting Hat - Multinomial logistic regression classification

The Harry Potter dataset was obtained from this blog. This tutorial is adapted in R. https://blog.jovian.ai/hogwarts-housing-with-logistic-regression-91faca42131e

Create a classification algorithm that serves as a Sorting Hat to predict which Hogwarts House a student belongs to based on the given features.

Loading packages

library(mice) # for imputing missing data
library(janitor) # for cleaning column names
library(GGally) # for plotting matrix of scatterplots
library(nnet) # for running multinomial logistic regression
library(tidyverse) # for reading csv file and data wrangling
library(caret) # for splitting the data into train and test sets
library(ggsci) # to get colour palettes

Explanation of dataset
Input features are:
  • Birthday
  • Best Hand
  • Arithmancy
  • Herbology
  • Defense Against the Dark Arts
  • Divination
  • Muggle Studies
  • Ancient Runes
  • History of Magic
  • Transfiguration
  • Potions
  • Care of Magical Creatures
  • Charms
  • Flying
Target feature is:
  • Hogwarts House

Convert categorical features into numerical. Categorical feature is Best Hand.

table(sorting_hat$`Best Hand`)
## 
##  Left Right 
##   790   810
# left is 0, right is 1

sorting_hat$`Best Hand` <- gsub("Left", 0, sorting_hat$`Best Hand`)
sorting_hat$`Best Hand` <- gsub("Right", 1, sorting_hat$`Best Hand`)

# convert Hogwarts House to factor
sorting_hat$`Hogwarts House` <- as.factor(sorting_hat$`Hogwarts House`)
table(sorting_hat$`Hogwarts House`)
## 
## Gryffindor Hufflepuff  Ravenclaw  Slytherin 
##        327        529        443        301

Impute missing values using mice

# keep desired columns
colnames(sorting_hat)
sorting_hat <- sorting_hat[,c(1,5:17)]

# check whether there are missing values NAs
summary(sorting_hat)
# there are a bunch of NAs

# clean column names to remove blank spaces
sorting_hat <- clean_names(sorting_hat)

# impute missing data
imputed_Data <- mice(sorting_hat, m=5, maxit = 50, method = 'pmm', seed = 500)
# check imputed data

Based on these plots, we look for features that have four different groups (Hogwarts house) and these features are Defense against the dark arts, Herbology, Ancient runes, Charms, Flying, Divination.

Splitting train and test datasets

index <- createDataPartition(sorting_hat_imputed$hogwarts_house, p = .70, list = FALSE)
train <- sorting_hat_imputed[index,]
test <- sorting_hat_imputed[-index,]

Model development

# Defining the reference
train$hogwarts_house <- relevel(train$hogwarts_house, ref = "Gryffindor")

# Training the multinomial model
multinom_model <- multinom(hogwarts_house ~ ., data = train)

The multinomial regression predicts the probability that a specific observation is part of a particular house.

Predicting and validating the model

# Predicting the values for train dataset
train$hogwarts_house_predicted <- predict(multinom_model, newdata = train, "class")

# Building classification table
tab <- table(train$hogwarts_house, train$hogwarts_house_predicted)

# Calculating accuracy - sum of diagonal elements divided by total obs
round((sum(diag(tab))/sum(tab))*100,2)
## [1] 98.04

The model accuracy is 98% in the training dataset.

Predicting Hogwarts House on the test dataset

# Predicting Hogwarts House for test dataset
test$hogwarts_house_predicted <- predict(multinom_model, newdata = test, "class")

# Building classification table
tab <- table(test$hogwarts_house, test$hogwarts_house_predicted)
